00:27:14,057 --> 00:27:15,391
I got the books!

732
00:27:15,475 --> 00:27:17,643
-Both sets?
-Yep!

733
00:27:17,727 --> 00:27:19,478
MIDGE: Wait, wait.

734
00:27:19,562 --> 00:27:21,355
Oh!

735
00:27:21,439 --> 00:27:23,816
-[SCREAMING]
-Let's get out of here.

736
00:27:23,900 --> 00:27:25,943
BOISE: Bunny, Mitzi, you got to move!

737
00:27:26,027 --> 00:27:28,112
You know, I'm getting
a little tired of everyone

738
00:27:28,196 --> 00:27:31,532
telling me what to do,
where to go, what a joke is.

739
00:27:31,616 --> 00:27:33,492
MITZI: Oh, crap! I lost an earring.

740
00:27:33,576 --> 00:27:34,659
We're being raided!

741
00:27:34,743 --> 00:27:36,494
What am I gonna do with one earring?!

742
00:27:36,578 --> 00:27:38,121
Two ears! I got two ears!

743
00:27:38,205 --> 00:27:40,707
-Stay down! Come on, come on.
-[MITZI GROANS]

744
00:27:40,791 --> 00:27:41,298
[FRANTIC CHATTER]

745
00:27:41,382 --> 00:27:43,001
WOMAN: Forget the feathers!
Just grab the pearls!

746
00:27:43,085 --> 00:27:44,836
-LENNY: Midge!
-I can't find my things.

747
00:27:44,920 --> 00:27:46,671
Buy more things. Let's go.

748
00:27:46,755 --> 00:27:48,840
[FRANTIC CHATTER CONTINUES]

749
00:27:51,718 --> 00:27:53,720
-Come with us.
-Nope.

750
00:27:53,804 --> 00:27:55,805
I'm fiddling on the <i>Titanic</i> tonight. Go.

751
00:27:55,889 --> 00:27:59,017
WOMAN: Hurry, hurry. Damn.
Go, go, go, go, go! Hurry!

752
00:27:59,101 --> 00:27:59,963
-[SHUDDERING]
-[MUTTERING]

753
00:28:00,047 --> 00:28:00,977
[SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE]

754
00:28:01,061 --> 00:28:03,521
MIDGE: My shoes, my feet. It's cold.

755
00:28:03,605 --> 00:28:05,857
LENNY: You'd be terrible to
go on the lam with, by the way.

756
00:28:05,941 --> 00:28:07,692
-Can't you carry me?
-Carry you?

757
00:28:07,776 --> 00:28:09,319
Yeah, you know, throw
me over your shoulder.

758
00:28:09,403 --> 00:28:11,279
Who am I, Santa Claus?
You're a young, strong woman.

759
00:28:11,363 --> 00:28:12,447
Here.

760
00:28:12,531 --> 00:28:13,990
-What do I do with this?
-[SIREN WAILING]

761
00:28:14,074 --> 00:28:16,034
Fill me in on what's going
on with Castro and the rebels.

762
00:28:16,118 --> 00:28:17,827
-Put it on your head.
-Where are you going?

763
00:28:17,911 --> 00:28:19,162
I have to get you to shelter.

764
00:28:19,246 --> 00:28:20,538
Aren't you gonna pay for the papers?

765
00:28:20,622 --> 00:28:22,165
-It's a snowstorm.
-So what?

766
00:28:22,249 --> 00:28:23,875
-The man has to make a living.
-How do you know?

767
00:28:23,959 --> 00:28:25,043
The newsstand could be a hobby.

768
00:28:25,127 --> 00:28:26,711
If I had my purse, I'd pay.

769
00:28:26,795 --> 00:28:29,130
-If I had your purse, I'd pay.
-Wh… What if there's a hell?

770
00:28:29,214 --> 00:28:31,424
-Oh, I don't believe this.
-What if the rabbis are wrong

771
00:28:31,508 --> 00:28:34,177
and there is a hell and this is
the moment our fate is decided?

772
00:28:34,261 --> 00:28:36,596
Believe me, honey, if there's
a hell, I'm the headliner.

773
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:38,306
Where are we going?

774
00:28:38,390 --> 00:28:40,308
[WIND HOWLING]

775
00:28:40,392 --> 00:28:42,394
♪♪

776
00:28:45,647 --> 00:28:48,483
[ELEGANT PIANO MUSIC PLAYING]

777
00:28:48,567 --> 00:28:50,443
[BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY]

778
00:28:50,527 --> 00:28:52,027
How you doing? You okay?

779
00:28:52,111 --> 00:28:53,737
Ten minutes in the elements.

780
00:28:53,821 --> 00:28:55,906
Do you need me to call
a hairdresser or a priest?

781
00:28:55,990 --> 00:28:57,366
I'm fine.

782
00:28:57,450 --> 00:28:59,576
-This place is nice.
-Carnegie Hall.

783
00:28:59,660 --> 00:29:01,495
Ooh, they're having a hat sale at B.
Altman's.

784
00:29:01,579 --> 00:29:03,205
If only I still had my employee discount,

785
00:29:03,289 --> 00:29:04,498
I'd get a discount on a discount.

786
00:29:04,582 --> 00:29:06,792
-Give me that.
-[GROANING]

787
00:29:06,876 --> 00:29:08,752
Good evening, Mr. Bruce.
Rough weather out there.

788
00:29:08,836 --> 00:29:10,045
It is indeed.

789
00:29:10,129 --> 00:29:11,630
You hear that? "Mr. Bruce."

790
00:29:11,714 --> 00:29:14,049
You play Carnegie Hall, you get "Mr.
Bruce."

791
00:29:14,133 --> 00:29:15,926
-Good evening, Mr. Bruce.
-[TAPS BUTTON]

792
00:29:16,010 --> 00:29:17,845
[BELL DINGS]

793
00:29:20,306 --> 00:29:23,100
-[INHALES SHARPLY] Whew.
-After you.

794
00:29:23,184 --> 00:29:26,103
-Ah.
-Well, what do you think?

795
00:29:26,187 --> 00:29:28,230
Very nice, Mr. Bruce.

796
00:29:28,314 --> 00:29:30,065
Carnegie Hall.

797
00:29:30,149 --> 00:29:33,235
So, drink? Food? Something absorbent?

798
00:29:33,319 --> 00:29:35,404
-Towel, please.
-[SNAPS FINGERS]

799
00:29:35,488 --> 00:29:37,531
Oh, I'm so sorry, girls.

800
00:29:37,615 --> 00:29:40,075
Wasn't supposed to end like this.

801
00:29:40,159 --> 00:29:41,410
Are you talking to your shoes?

802
00:29:41,494 --> 00:29:43,078
No. Shh.

803
00:29:43,162 --> 00:29:45,414
-[SHOES DROP TO FLOOR]
-That's okay.

804
00:29:45,498 --> 00:29:47,791
I'm gonna have a very
serious talk later with my dickie.

805
00:29:47,875 --> 00:29:51,128
-Dickie? Like…
-Yes.

806
00:29:51,212 --> 00:29:52,546
-Not…
-No.

807
00:29:52,630 --> 00:29:54,381
-Nice.
-It was the funniest garment

808
00:29:54,465 --> 00:29:56,467
I could come up with in the moment.

809
00:30:04,600 --> 00:30:06,143
Keeping a safe distance?

810
00:30:06,227 --> 00:30:08,561
Respectful distance, I'd like to say.

811
00:30:08,645 --> 00:30:10,813
Are you afraid of me
'cause I talk to my shoes?

812
00:30:10,897 --> 00:30:12,815
Some men find that wildly attractive.

813
00:30:12,899 --> 00:30:14,442
I think there are many things about you

814
00:30:14,526 --> 00:30:17,403
men would find wildly attractive.

815
00:30:24,077 --> 00:30:25,870
You know you can sit on the entire chair.

816
00:30:25,954 --> 00:30:27,497
I'm fine.

817
00:30:28,623 --> 00:30:30,166
You look like one of the Wallendas,

818
00:30:30,250 --> 00:30:31,667
balancing there like that.

819
00:30:31,751 --> 00:30:36,297
It… I'm wearing… I'm good.

820
00:30:36,381 --> 00:30:37,715
Your what?

821
00:30:37,799 --> 00:30:39,592
What are you wearing?

822
00:30:40,635 --> 00:30:42,303
My show corset.

823
00:30:42,387 --> 00:30:44,013
[LAUGHS]

824
00:30:44,097 --> 00:30:46,557
-You have a show corset?
-Yes.

825
00:30:46,641 --> 00:30:50,436
How is this different from,
say, your dentist corset?

826
00:30:50,520 --> 00:30:52,688
It's much more likely to suffocate me.

827
00:30:52,772 --> 00:30:54,315
-It's also prettier.
-Yep.

828
00:30:54,399 --> 00:30:57,318
It's always the pretty
ones who try to kill you.

829
00:31:07,078 --> 00:31:08,704
Oh, boy.

830
00:31:08,788 --> 00:31:12,458
-What? I did not plan this.
-Getting me back here?

831
00:31:12,542 --> 00:31:14,919
Innocent.
Get Roy Cohn on the phone right now.

832
00:31:15,003 --> 00:31:17,296
You mean you didn't alter the atmosphere,

833
00:31:17,380 --> 00:31:19,006
causing it to snow,
and then organize a raid

834
00:31:19,090 --> 00:31:20,758
at the exact moment I came offstage?

835
00:31:20,842 --> 00:31:22,009
What, I'm not important enough

836
00:31:22,093 --> 00:31:24,178
to go through all that trouble for?

837
00:31:25,471 --> 00:31:29,725
You are more important than God.

838
00:31:30,767 --> 00:31:32,185
You paid attention.

839
00:31:34,688 --> 00:31:36,481
To you?

840
00:31:36,565 --> 00:31:38,066
Always.

841
00:31:45,198 --> 00:31:46,950
Midge?

842
00:31:47,034 --> 00:31:48,368
Yeah?

843
00:31:49,369 --> 00:31:52,080
I got to see the show corset.

844
00:31:52,164 --> 00:31:53,915
-Lenny.
-I'm sorry.

845
00:31:53,999 --> 00:31:55,667
I'm an observer of the human condition.

846
00:31:55,751 --> 00:31:57,586
It's the way God made me.

847
00:32:11,308 --> 00:32:12,517
Okay.

848
00:32:12,601 --> 00:32:15,103
-If we do this…
-Oops.

849
00:32:15,187 --> 00:32:17,105
If we take our clothes off

850
00:32:17,189 --> 00:32:21,568
and we do some very blue
things in this very blue room…

851
00:32:21,652 --> 00:32:24,112
Wow, do I not know
which way this is going.

852
00:32:24,196 --> 00:32:26,698
I need you to look me in
the eye first and promise

853
00:32:26,782 --> 00:32:30,285
that you will never, ever forget

854
00:32:30,369 --> 00:32:34,456
that I am very, very funny.

855
00:32:36,166 --> 00:32:37,709
First and foremost.

856
00:32:37,793 --> 00:32:39,753
I'm serious, Lenny.

857
00:32:55,476 --> 00:32:58,979
I will be laughing
through the entire thing.

858
00:32:59,063 --> 00:33:01,065
I promise.

859
00:33:02,108 --> 00:33:05,736
[BLOSSOM DEARIE:
"SOMEONE TO WATCH OVER ME"]

860
00:33:05,820 --> 00:33:09,198
<i>♪ There's a saying old,
says that love is blind ♪</i>

861
00:33:10,991 --> 00:33:15,079
<i>♪ Still we're often told,
"Seek and ye shall find" ♪</i>

862
00:33:17,081 --> 00:33:19,416
<i>♪ So I'm going to seek a certain lad ♪</i>

863
00:33:19,500 --> 00:33:23,254
<i>♪ I've had in mind ♪</i>

864
00:33:25,923 --> 00:33:27,675
Yep.

865
00:33:29,009 --> 00:33:30,761
Just like mine.

866
00:33:30,845 --> 00:33:34,014
<i>♪ I'd like to add his initial ♪</i>

867
00:33:34,098 --> 00:33:36,976
<i>♪ To my monogram ♪</i>

868
00:33:40,771 --> 00:33:42,732
<i>♪ Tell me ♪</i>

869
00:33:44,066 --> 00:33:47,319
<i>♪ Where is the shepherd ♪</i>

870
00:33:47,403 --> 00:33:50,864
<i>♪ For this lost lamb? ♪</i>

871
00:33:50,948 --> 00:33:52,324
I lied.

872
00:33:52,408 --> 00:33:54,702
I'm only gonna laugh at the end.

873
00:33:57,329 --> 00:34:01,374
<i>♪ There's a somebody ♪</i>

874
00:34:01,458 --> 00:34:04,711
<i>♪ I'm longing to see ♪</i>

875
00:34:06,838 --> 00:34:09,340
<i>♪ I hope that he ♪</i>

876
00:34:09,424 --> 00:34:11,676
-LENNY: Nope.
-<i>♪ Turns out to be ♪</i>

877
00:34:11,760 --> 00:34:13,845
I'll be right back.

878
00:34:16,014 --> 00:34:20,810
<i>♪ Someone to watch ♪</i>

879
00:34:20,894 --> 00:34:23,855
<i>♪ Over me ♪</i>

880
00:34:31,696 --> 00:34:32,780
[LIGHT BUZZING]

881
00:34:32,864 --> 00:34:36,492
<i>♪ I'm a little lamb ♪</i>

882
00:34:36,576 --> 00:34:39,579
<i>♪ Who's lost in the wood ♪</i>

883
00:34:41,915 --> 00:34:44,542
<i>♪ I know I could ♪</i>

884
00:34:44,626 --> 00:34:47,128
-[PHONE RINGING]
-<i>♪ Always be good ♪</i>

885
00:34:47,212 --> 00:34:48,921
LENNY: Hello?

886
00:34:49,005 --> 00:34:50,923
[PHONE CONVERSATION
CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY]

887
00:34:51,007 --> 00:34:54,927
<i>♪ To one who'd watch ♪</i>

888
00:34:55,011 --> 00:34:58,514
<i>-♪ Over me… ♪</i>
-LENNY: Goodbye.

889
00:34:58,598 --> 00:35:01,392
So, apparently, being Mr. Bruce means

890
00:35:01,476 --> 00:35:03,102
you're the one who has to bail out

891
00:35:03,186 --> 00:35:04,729
the slow runners after a raid.

892
00:35:04,813 --> 00:35:08,858
So I was thinking… That is not for you.

893
00:35:08,942 --> 00:35:10,735
Lenny, what…

894
00:35:10,819 --> 00:35:12,695
You don't need to worry about that.

895
00:35:12,779 --> 00:35:15,406
-But…
-All is well.

896
00:35:15,490 --> 00:35:16,865
I promise.

897
00:35:16,949 --> 00:35:18,241
Now, get dressed.

898
00:35:18,325 --> 00:35:20,243
We'll go spring the
riffraff, and then I'll take you

899
00:35:20,327 --> 00:35:22,746
for some truly terrible
Chinese food, okay?

900
00:35:24,289 --> 00:35:27,709
<i>♪ Someone ♪</i>

901
00:35:27,793 --> 00:35:29,878
<i>♪ To watch ♪</i>

902
00:35:29,962 --> 00:35:33,924
<i>♪ Over me ♪</i>

903
00:35:40,180 --> 00:35:42,307
[SONG ENDS]

904
00:35:42,391 --> 00:35:44,017
-Abe! Abe!
-Hmm?

905
00:35:44,101 --> 00:35:45,560
I didn't know you were still here.

906
00:35:45,644 --> 00:35:47,771
Someone called a while
ago, said you needed to get

907
00:35:47,855 --> 00:35:49,773
-to the hospital immediately.
-What? Who?

908
00:35:49,857 --> 00:35:51,775
-I don't know. I…
-He's dead. Is he dead?

909
00:35:51,859 --> 00:35:53,443
-Oh, my God.
-I don't know.

910
00:35:53,527 --> 00:35:55,487
They just said to hurry.

911
00:35:55,571 --> 00:35:57,572
I will bite your fingers off, Isobel.

912
00:35:57,656 --> 00:35:59,324
It's not Isobel, Dody.

913
00:35:59,408 --> 00:36:00,784
-It's Abe.
-Abe?

914
00:36:00,868 --> 00:36:02,869
-What time is it?
-It's very late.

915
00:36:02,953 --> 00:36:04,746
I have to get to the hospital.

916
00:36:04,830 --> 00:36:06,748
You should go home.

917
00:36:06,832 --> 00:36:08,333
Thank you for your help.

918
00:36:08,417 --> 00:36:10,460
You are a true Sancho Panza.

919
00:36:12,462 --> 00:36:14,756
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
<i>Phone call for Dr. O'Connell.</i>

920
00:36:14,840 --> 00:36:18,343
<i>Dr. O'Connell, you have a
phone call at the nurses' station.</i>

921
00:36:18,427 --> 00:36:20,012
I…

922
00:36:21,179 --> 00:36:23,056
What kept you?

923
00:36:23,140 --> 00:36:24,766
I… But you're alive.

924
00:36:24,850 --> 00:36:26,017
I am. Yes.

925
00:36:26,101 --> 00:36:27,352
You're not dead.

926
00:36:27,436 --> 00:36:29,521
No, I'm not.

927
00:36:29,605 --> 00:36:32,315
I just… The call… I figured…

928
00:36:32,399 --> 00:36:33,649
You hoping for a different outcome?

929
00:36:33,733 --> 00:36:35,943
No. I'm fine with it, obviously.

930
00:36:36,027 --> 00:36:37,361
I tried to call you.

931
00:36:37,445 --> 00:36:39,780
Some disgruntled employee
rushed me off the phone.

932
00:36:39,864 --> 00:36:43,242
Oh. Well, that's… terrific, really.

933
00:36:43,326 --> 00:36:46,078
[CHUCKLES] Just surprised.

934
00:36:46,162 --> 00:36:48,080
Who's this? Do I know her?

935
00:36:48,164 --> 00:36:49,373
SHIRLEY: Oh, this is Mei.

936
00:36:49,457 --> 00:36:50,791
It's so wonderful.

937
00:36:50,875 --> 00:36:53,252
Do you know that now
hospitals hire mah-jongg players

938
00:36:53,336 --> 00:36:55,337
to distract you from impending death?

939
00:36:55,421 --> 00:36:56,380
-ABE: Really?
-What?

940
00:36:56,464 --> 00:36:57,631
-She asked. I froze.
-Ah, geez.

941
00:36:57,715 --> 00:36:59,258
She tipped me, though,
so I can pay you back.

942
00:36:59,342 --> 00:37:00,259
That's nice.

943
00:37:00,343 --> 00:37:01,218
What's that, Abe?

944
00:37:01,302 --> 00:37:02,678
-What?
-In your hand.

945
00:37:02,762 --> 00:37:04,388
Oh, it's nothing.

946
00:37:04,472 --> 00:37:05,681
You're holding it very tightly.

947
00:37:05,765 --> 00:37:07,266
It's just, uh…

948
00:37:07,350 --> 00:37:09,226
It says "Moishe's obituary."

949
00:37:09,310 --> 00:37:11,353
-You wrote my obituary?
-No.

950
00:37:11,437 --> 00:37:13,814
You wrote something and
titled it "Moishe's Obituary"?

951
00:37:13,898 --> 00:37:15,107
[ABE SIGHS] I…

952
00:37:15,191 --> 00:37:16,859
You couldn't get the
guy who wrote Einstein's?

953
00:37:16,943 --> 00:37:21,280
ABE: No. I just… Yes. I wrote something.

954
00:37:21,364 --> 00:37:23,574
Well, what were you going
to do rushing in here like that?

955
00:37:23,658 --> 00:37:25,951
-I think I was going to read it.
-To me?

956
00:37:26,035 --> 00:37:27,369
-Yes.
-While I was unconscious?

957
00:37:27,453 --> 00:37:28,704
Or dead. Yes.

958
00:37:28,788 --> 00:37:30,956
-I'd like to hear it.
-What? No.

959
00:37:31,040 --> 00:37:32,416
-I'm a little curious, too.
-Same here.

960
00:37:32,500 --> 00:37:33,584
You work for the hospital.

961
00:37:33,668 --> 00:37:34,960
-You don't get a vote.
-MOISHE: Abe.

962
00:37:35,044 --> 00:37:37,838
Well, it… it was just a first draft,

963
00:37:37,922 --> 00:37:40,925
so I hadn't finished it, but…

964
00:37:42,343 --> 00:37:46,138
I just talked about your
father and the pickle cart.

965
00:37:46,222 --> 00:37:47,848
We all know that story.

966
00:37:47,932 --> 00:37:49,141
So, uh…

967
00:37:49,225 --> 00:37:52,143
You started a clothing
manufacturing business.

968
00:37:52,227 --> 00:37:53,895
There was no Roth.

969
00:37:53,979 --> 00:37:55,897
It was all you. Gave you full credit.

970
00:37:55,981 --> 00:37:57,440
-Thank you.
-ABE: Oh. Uh,

971
00:37:57,524 --> 00:38:00,610
Moishe brought over
the 13 Jews, saved them.

972
00:38:00,694 --> 00:38:03,613
Very nice paragraph about that.

973
00:38:03,697 --> 00:38:06,741
Good… Good placement. And, uh…

974
00:38:06,825 --> 00:38:09,619
Oh, I found a typo.

975
00:38:09,703 --> 00:38:11,996
I just found another. Who has a pen?

